Reasoning: The paper deals with operator precedence grammars and their equivalent operational formalism for defining FLs. FLs are a well-known topic in formal language theory and are closely related to pushdown automata, which suggests that the paper could belong to the cs.FL (Formal Languages and Automata Theory) sub-category. The paper also introduces Floyd automata, which are a type of pushdown automata, and discusses their closure properties, which could make it relevant to the cs.PL (Programming Languages) sub-category. The paper also mentions the use of FLs for model checking, which could make it relevant to the cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the extension of FLs to deal with infinite strings, which could make it relevant to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the relationship between FLs and visibly pushdown languages, which could make it relevant to the cs.FM (Formal Methods) sub-category.
